{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17588856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17588856"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:12:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15182"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15182"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.29,0,0.11,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7873"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62755"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7873"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48203"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8138"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19196"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19197"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62755"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA varicocele is a dilatation of the veins within the pampiniform plexus. This collection of some ten veins drains the testis and the epididymis. There is a similar network in females where the pampiniform plexus drains the ovary into the ovarian vein.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In males, which one of the following statements about varicoceles is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["There is spontaneous resolution without treatment","More commonly occur on the right side","Result from increased arterial blood flow","Typically present with acute pain","Defective venous valves contribute to formation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVaricoceles occur due to abnormal dilatation of the pampiniform plexus veins. They can be found in some 20% of the male population. \u003Cstrong\u003EDefective venous valves\u003C/strong\u003E are a key contributing factor, allowing retrograde blood flow and venous congestion. Varicoceles are \u003Cstrong\u003Emore common on the left side\u003C/strong\u003E (80-90% of cases) due to the perpendicular entry of the left testicular vein into the left renal vein, whereas the right testicular vein enters the inferior vena cava at an oblique angle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased arterial flow\u003C/strong\u003E is not involved in varicocele formation. Varicoceles typically cause a dull ache rather than \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute pain\u003C/strong\u003E. They do not typically \u003Cstrong\u003Eresolve spontaneously\u003C/strong\u003E and may require intervention if causing symptoms or fertility issues. In most instances varicoceles cause few symptoms and can be left well alone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A varicocele is an abnormal dilatation of the pampiniform plexus veins, occurring most commonly on the left side due to anatomical differences.","Left-sided varicoceles occur due to the left testicular vein\u0027s perpendicular entry into the left renal vein.","Defective venous valves can contribute to varicocele formation by allowing retrograde blood flow."],"references":["Conze J, Klinge U, Schumpelick V. Hernias. In: Holzheimer RG, Mannick JA, editors. Surgical Treatment: Evidence-Based and Problem-Oriented. Munich: Zuckschwerdt; 2001. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK6888/","Leslie SW, Sajjad H, Siref LE. Varicocele. [Updated 2023 Nov 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448113/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48203"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15182"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48203"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T18:01:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-18T18:02:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7873"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62755"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relatio